# Cridora v2 — safe editing

## Protect working code

- Change only what the user asked for. No drive-by refactors, formatting sweeps, or renames.
- Do not modify “known good” modules to add unrelated features. Prefer **new files** in clear locations.
- Do not change public API shapes (Django URLs/serializers, React component props) without updating all call sites in the **same** change.

## Isolate features (failure containment)

- **Backend (`backend/`)**: add logic in dedicated modules (`services/`, `selectors/`, feature-specific modules or apps). Keep views thin: validate → one service call → response.
- **Frontend (`frontend/`)**: add UI under `src/features/<feature>/` (or project equivalent). Avoid touching global router/layout/auth unless requested.
- Never grow unrelated code in shared `utils` or middleware for one feature unless unavoidable; keep those edits minimal.

## Django / database

- **Never edit applied migrations.** Add new migration files only.
- Production is on **Railway**: internal `DATABASE_URL` may not work from local Windows. Use `docs/RAILWAY_MIGRATIONS.md` for SSH migrate and env vars (`VITE_API_ORIGIN`, `DJANGO_PUBLIC_BASE_URL`, media).

## Deploy awareness

- Git may deploy to Railway. Keep changes small and committable. Schema changes require migrations in the same delivery as the code.

## If unclear

- Stop and ask the user rather than guessing or refactoring broadly.
